<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-04-28T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-04-28T21:00:00-05:00" n="805" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d805">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.796/200: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Second Secretary of Legation in China</hi>
                                (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi></persName>)
                                <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-04-29T10:00:00+08:00">April 29, 1935—10
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received April 29—5:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>85. I am reliably informed that within past 3 days a meeting of
                            representatives of the Foreign Office, the Ministry of Communications
                                <pb facs="0913" n="801" xml:id="pg_801"/> and the Military Affairs
                            Commission called to discuss questions of possible cooperation by China
                            in development of overseas transportation, decided Chinese Government
                            would not for the present grant landing rights to any foreign aviation
                            concerns because of fear that concessions to western airline companies
                            would make it impossible to refuse similar requests from Japanese.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Atcheson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>